Requirements - Whenever you make a thrown weapon attack, the weapon you throw returns back to your hand immediately, allowing you to continuously make attacks with the same weapon(s) in the same turn.{% hint style="warning" %}
If a weapon's special effect requires being on the opponent to function (such as exotic weapons like nets), then you cannot ricochet them.
{% endhint %}You also ignore the attack penalty from using thrown weapons in their second range increment.

Requirements - Choose one: slash, pierce or crushYou can use the default special attacks of these weapon types (cleave/lacerate, lunge/pierce defense, backbreaker/concussive strike) at-will.You also gain a new one depending on the type you chose, usable 1/combat.Slash: Great Cleave - Attack all creatures within reachPierce: Impale - Creature struck provokes an AoO if they move by the start of your next turn.Crush: Pulverize - Stagger on hit (fort negates)The default and newly acquired special attacks also add your level to damage.{% hint style="success" %}
If you have the unarmed combatant feat, then you can apply the effects of weapon focus (crush) to the special attacks granted by it.
{% endhint %}

Requirements - As a swift action, increase the DC of an instantaneous spell you cast this turn by 2 if you include any non-minion allies (including yourself) in its AoE.{% hint style="danger" %}
If you have an ability to effectively not include allies in an AoE, then you do not get the bonus of this feat.
If the ally is immune or resistant to the effect, then you do not get the bonus of this feat.
{% endhint %}

Requirements - Int +0Your spells with the [curse] descriptor can also be cast on items. The first creature to activate or put on this item is afflicted with the curse (save negates). If the save is successful, the curse is lifted. For items that aren't activated or worn (such as a rock) the creature must possess the item or at least 1 minute for the curse to take hold.With curses that allow for a creative uses, the parameters must be set at the time the spell is cast.{% hint style="info" %}
SPECIAL: You can only curse three items at a time. When a curse afflicts a creature that plays with your protected items, it no longer counts against this total. If you cast another latent curse with 3 already active, you choose which item is no longer cursed.You have an innate sense when one of your latent curse spells is triggered.
{% endhint %}

Requirements - Int +1You can fire the effect of a spell with the [healing] tag using the range of a ranged weapon. If the healing spell can target multiple creatures, you can make as many attacks as you like, but cannot target an ally more than once.You can also choose to target a space to be the origin point of your spell.{% hint style="success" %}
As part of using this feat, you can swap to a ranged weapon, then swap back to your staff.
{% endhint %}

Requirements - Level 3, Cha +0You get a beast companion minion as per the beast trainer class feature.{% hint style="info" %}
Minion: Its level is limited to 1/3 your level.
{% endhint %}

{% hint style="danger" %}
A teamwork feat requires more than one creature to possess in order to function, usually providing some kind of synergistic effect. The wording of these feats often include "all allies," but it only applies to allies with the feat.
{% endhint %}

All knowledge uses int.
What you know. Knowledge is broken up into many different skills based on subject and each one has a subsection dedicated to monster lore of specific types of creatures. Monster lore isn’t its own skill, but it has its own functions separate from the rest of individual knowledge skills. If a subject or creature falls into multiple categories, then players can choose whichever they like more, but an individual character can't roll multiple checks with different skills.{% hint style="warning" %}
If you want to know who an individual creature is and their relevance to the world, rather than their stats and abilities, the DC is usually dependent on how popular they are. Typically (22-lvl) with additional reductions to the DC if they are famous, or in a position of power. This could also include increases to the DC if they work to keep their identity and exploits hidden, or live remotely.
{% endhint %}Monster LoreAdventurers are assumed to know basic things about monsters, like how constructs lack of anatomy grant them resistance to many effects or the properties of incorporeal creatures. Monster lore checks are for figuring out more information about specific monsters. Monster stat blocks are broken up into sections. Basic stats (saves, HP and AC), offense traits (breath weapons, dangerous auras, prominent spells), defense traits (healing abilities, elemental resistances), other traits (extra senses, extra movement options, out of combat abilities) and weaknesses/deep lore (lich's phylactery, vampires not appearing in mirrors). Rolling a monster lore check is something you can do as a free action once per turn. It is assumed that you also vocalize what you learn to your team. The base DC of a monster lore check is (10+creature's lvl). By succeeding on a monster lore check, you can figure out a creature's basic stats and one other category. Every 5 over the DC you roll, you figure out another category. If a creature has nothing in a category, you choose another.Creatures with the [unique] tag in their entry increase monster lore DC by 5. Humanoids with class levels by default are assumed to have the [unique] tag.{% tabs %}
{% tab title="Arcana" %}
The default skill whenever magic is involved. Common uses include figuring out what spell someone is casting, determining the magical properties of items and identifying the effects of persistent spells.
Identifies dragons with monster lore.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Alchemy" %}
The blanket skill for most of DnD (mad) science. Used for the creation of potions, poisons and other strange but useful concoctions.
Identifies oozes with monster lore.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Cryptozoology" %}
Used in the knowledge of creatures that should not be. Cryptozoologists are particularly astute at remembering legends that pertain to creatures, and gleaning hoaxes.
Identifies aberrations and cryptids with monster lore.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Engineering" %}
Used to determine things related to structures, such as building them, finding weaknesses or the ability to make basic assumptions about its design (ex. a factory this large needs an exhaust vent somewhere). It can also be used to identify technology such as elevators, vehicles and other mechanical objects.
Identifies constructs using monster lore.
{% endtab %}
{% endtabs %}{% tabs %}
{% tab title="History" %}
Used to recall events that happened in the past and prominent historical figures. Historians are good at identifying the flags of fallen nations, reading in dead languages and recognizing relics from the past.
Does not have a specific creature type you can use monster lore with. Can be a suitable substitute for famous or infamous creatures hundreds or thousands of years old.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Local" %}
Used to know about cities, countries, individuals. Specifically their culture, traditions, legends, government, laws, customs, politics and prominent organizationsIdentifies humanoids and giants with monster lore.Special: When using monster lore against humanoids that have class levels, you learn information about the class the creature possesses.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Nature" %}
Used to detect oddities in the natural order and how to restore it. Can also be used to determine the weather, identify naturally occurring things like ores and flowers and elements unique to the feywilds.Identifies plants, fey and beasts using monster lore. {% endtab %}{% tab title="Planes" %}
Used to determine the nature of other planes. Can also be used to determine the destination of portals and where they might be located.Identifies fiends, celestials and elementals.
{% endtab %}{% tab title="Religion" %}
Used in understanding/identifying gods and their followers. Church hierarchies, religious practices, symbols and scripture are all covered by this skill.Identifies undead with monster lore.
{% endtab %}
{% endtabs %}NerdWhen you succeed on a monster lore check, gain knowledge about an additional category.Lore DumpYou can rapidly assess the battlefield and communicate your knowledge. You can roll an unlimited number of monster lore checks each turn.

